{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.06,0.02,0.09,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"17"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109755"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/17"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92154"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109755"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being retrieved from a house party where he became increasingly unresponsive. His friend reports he has been vomiting, which was initially attributed to alcohol intoxication. He has no known medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 96/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is 8/15. He is taking deep breaths and his breath has a fruity odour with a concurrent smell of alcohol. His mouth is dry and his vomitus contains brown fluid without blood. His abdomen is diffusely tender but not rigid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Venous blood gas","Blood alcohol concentration","HbA1c","Fasting glucose","Urine ketones"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with altered consciousness, Kussmaul breathing (deep respirations), and fruity breath, strongly suggesting diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). The presentation is complicated by likely concurrent alcohol use, which can precipitate DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous blood gas\u003C/strong\u003E analysis is the most appropriate initial investigation as it provides rapid, comprehensive information about acid-base status, glucose level, and electrolytes. It will confirm DKA by demonstrating high glucose levels, metabolic acidosis with an elevated anion gap, and typically elevated potassium levels. The severity of DKA can be assessed by the degree of acidosis and bicarbonate depletion. Importantly, venous blood gas is nearly as accurate as arterial blood gas for pH and bicarbonate assessment, while being less painful and easier to obtain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood alcohol concentration\u003C/strong\u003E measurement is relevant but less urgent, as the clinical features suggest a more serious underlying metabolic derangement that requires immediate identification and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHbA1c\u003C/strong\u003E reflects average glucose levels over three months, and while it is applicable for longer-term management, it does not assist with the immediate diagnosis or management of an acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate in this emergency setting where the patient is acutely unwell and requires immediate assessment. What is needed is a random glucose measurement, which would be obtained as part of the venous blood gas analysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine ketones\u003C/strong\u003E would be difficult to obtain in an unconscious patient and are less reliable than blood ketones, which would be measured as part of a broader set of investigations after the initial arterial blood gas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venous blood gas analysis rapidly provides critical information about acid-base status, glucose, and electrolytes in suspected diabetic ketoacidosis.","The clinical triad of Kussmaul breathing, fruity breath, and altered consciousness strongly suggests diabetic ketoacidosis.","Diabetic ketoacidosis commonly presents with no prior diabetes history and can be precipitated by alcohol use."],"references":["Nyenwe EA, Kitabche AE. The evolution of diabetic ketoacidosis: An update of its etiology, pathogenesis and management. Met Clin Exp 2016; 65:507-21. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26975543/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92154"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92154"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-26T04:05:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-26T04:05:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"17"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109755"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","pos